prompt:
Write an academic analysis of how historical narratives are being reinterpreted through contemporary political and social lenses. Requirements:
- Length: 1,500–2,000 words; scholarly tone.
- Structure:
  Abstract (150–200 words);
  Introduction (scope; definitions of ideologisation, instrumentalisation, silenced narratives);
  Theoretical framework (memory studies, nationalism, postcolonial theory);
  Comparative case studies (≥4 regions across the Americas, Europe, Africa/Asia) covering:
    a) ideologisation in curricula/public discourse,
    b) instrumentalisation of the past in elections, foreign policy, transitional justice,
    c) efforts to reclaim erased/silenced narratives (indigenous, subaltern, gendered, diasporic);
  Commemorative practices (monuments, museums, anniversaries) and feedback into historiography;
  Digital memory and platform politics;
  Counterarguments and methodological caveats;
  Conclusion (implications for scholarship and policy).
- Evidence: Cite ≥12 recent scholarly sources (2018–2025). Include ≥2 monument/renaming controversies and ≥2 textbook/curriculum reforms (e.g., 1619 vs. 1776; Poland/IPN; Comfort Women debates; South Africa TRC; Russia’s war memory; Latin American memory laws).
- Presentation: Include one comparative table mapping actors → mechanisms → outcomes; use Chicago footnotes or APA; provide references with DOIs/links.
- Notes: Clarify contested terminology; identify biases and epistemic limits.
